Author::::Sue Everett
DateTime::::2016-01-09T08:43:47Z
It was the carte blanche policy given to farmers that originally created much of the problems we see today with waterwater and mud ending up in people's front rooms.  it is a fact that the predecessors to the environment agency along with the ministry of Agriculture actively promoted the drainage of agricultural land, especially infloodplains, facilitated by river dredgingdredging done by the EA's predecessors. I was told that the National Rivers Authority actually used to fly over floodplains looking for wet bits that could be drained so allowing farmers to do what they want on their land at anytime to speed water off land which should never have been drained in the first placeplace. Truss's decision is absolute Madness when we should be putting some of that drainage into reverse. Onee of the most obscene things I ever saw was in the Nene Washes in Cambridgeshire in the early 1980ss; the Nene Washes is an area of land designed for storing flood water to prevent Peterborough from floodingflooding. However one area had been in banked ditched and was being actively pumped so that a farmer who had land within the washers could grow carrots there; fortunately this is one area where that kind of thing is no longer happening and where the conservation ngos particularly RSPB now have large holdings. Also during that time we were still losing the last boggy fields and flashes on hillsides and in floodplains to improve the land for intensification either for arable or reseeded leys. About 15 years ago I had a privilege to look at some of the original 1960s land use survey that Alice Coleman spearheadedspearheaded - at that time I was involved in restoring flower rich grassland arable on claylands in West Buckinghamshire and those areas were very difficult to restore because they should never have been ploughed in the first place ... in the 1960s all that area was permanent grassland because it was stupid to do anything else with it. The drainage and ploughing of that area was another example where carte blanche land drainage for so called agricultural improvement was bad for farming, devastating for soils and bad for floodin .. But there are just so many examples of this. Of course the big consequence was for wildlife of flower rich boggy places such as the wild flowers, butterflies, snipe, redshank and the curlew. We started to see the tide begin to turn with Andrew Lees in the 1980s standing firm over the proposed drainage of Halvergate Marshes, thank goodness. This marked the first steps towards what we now know as the agri-environment schemes which remain the most important life line we have for protecting wildlife and countryside and arguably stopping some of the stupid things that many farmers will do unless they are paid not to. I now fear that the small gains made over the past 30 years are under threat.



