Author::::nonNTT
DateTime::::2016-01-08T22:16:26Z
The less sheep the better. The main destroyer of biodiversity in the uplands is the artificial nitrogen used to grow rye grass for sheep grazing. A profitable exercise, but only just; subsidies tip the balance. Take away the nitrogen (which has a huge carbon footprint) and all the wild flowers plus all the invertebrates, will slowly return. Sheep must be reduced or got rid of. But keep the farming communities by using the subsidies to return the uplands to a more natural state – native woodlands; wood pastures alongside restored and active peat bogs on the moors freed up from intensive grouse ‘farming’.  If you are worried about too much scrub taking over, then let cattle roam. They love to browse, in fact they are woodland animals by nature. Result: less compacted soils; more humus; more sponge-like sphagnum mosses; more rain absorbent peat; more statements of the obvious about runoff and peak flows with a reduced probability of overtopping flood barriers. A one per cent reduction will do. That translates every time, no matter how much rain, to a few more dry homes than would have otherwise been the case.



