Author::::voteforfarmers
DateTime::::2016-01-08T20:47:53Z
Not sure you quite understand how this sort of drainage works - the water doesn't stay in the ditch it drains into the river system all year round so that the field is never waterlogged. If we have a massive deluge of rain and it lands on a dry (drained) field it doesn't enter the ditch immediately, it has to percolate through the soil to the drainage system. This takes a certain amount of time and though it is quite quick it is no where near as fast as the time it takes for surface water to run off a waterlogged field into the river system. That said I'm not altogether for drainage of all fields. There is a place for wet meadows that will hold far more water than an average field, however these will end up needing funding from somewhere as they, by their very nature, are not very agriculturally productive and therefore won't pay the rent!



